  <title translate="true">bridge</title>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; color:#000000;" translate="true">A non-closed traverse is a </text><text style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold; color:#000000;" translate="true">bridge</text><text style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; color:#000000;" translate="true"> if the only path of vectors connecting the traverse&apos;s two endpoints is the traverse itself. &#160;In Walls the operation of </text><text style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic; color:#000000;" translate="true">floating</text><text style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; color:#000000;" translate="true"> a traverse -- that is, making it conform to an independently adjusted loop system -- will sometimes, in effect, turn other traverses into bridges. See </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="Terminology" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; color:#000000;" translate="true">Network Terminology</link><text style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; color:#000000;" translate="true">.</text></para>
  </body>
